Your task is to write a Jest test case that exposes a specific mutation in a JavaScript/TypeScript project.

MUTATION DETAILS
The mutation affects the following file:
sinks/drain.js
Here is the full content of that file (shown with a <PLACEHOLDER> marker):
'use strict'

module.exports = function drain (op, done) {
  var read, abort

  // Declared here so that it captures the drain's stack trace
  var doneLackingErr
  if (!done) {
       doneLackingErr = new Error("")

  }

  function sink (_read) {
    read = _read
    if(abort) return sink.abort()
    //this function is much simpler to write if you
    //just use recursion, but by using a while loop
    //we do not blow the stack if the stream happens to be sync.
    <PLACEHOLDER>
        var loop = true, cbed = false
        while(loop) {
          cbed = false
          read(null, function (end, data) {
            cbed = true
            if(end = end || abort) {
              loop = false
              if(done) done(end === true ? null : end)
              else if(end && end !== true) {
                console.warn(doneLackingErr)
                throw end
              }
            }
            else if(op && false === op(data) || abort) {
              loop = false
              read(abort || true, done || function () {})
            }
            else if(!loop){
              next()
            }
          })
          if(!cbed) {
            loop = false
            return
          }
        }
      })()
  }

  sink.abort = function (err, cb) {
    if('function' == typeof err)
      cb = err, err = true
    abort = err || true
    if(read) return read(abort, cb || function () {})
  }

  return sink
}

In the original code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

-           var loop = true, cbed = false
In the mutated code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

+           var loop = true, cbed = true


YOUR TASK
Write one Jest test file that:
    1. Passes when run against the original code.
    2. Fails when run against the mutated code.
    3. Tests the behavior of the mutated file in a way that reliably detects the mutation.
The test will be saved at the following path, relative to this test-generation project’s root:
llm-cache/anthropic_claude-sonnet-4.6/temp_0.5/withoutTests/cached/artifacts/pull-stream/attempt_1/pending_category/mutant-1042f74/testCase.test.ts

ALLOWED LIBRARIES
You may use:
    1. Any built-in Node.js modules (e.g., fs, path, crypto, etc.).

You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the change is:
- Original: `var loop = true, cbed = false`
- Mutated: `var loop = true, cbed = true`

The `cbed` variable tracks whether the callback was called synchronously. If `cbed` starts as `true` instead of `false`, the check `if(!cbed)` at the end of the while loop will never be `false` initially, which changes the control flow.

Specifically, when `cbed` starts as `true`, after the `read` call, if the callback was NOT called synchronously (async stream), the code checks `if(!cbed)` - but since `cbed` was initialized to `true`, even if the callback hasn't been called yet, `!cbed` would be `false` and `next()` wouldn't be called. Wait, let me re-read...

Actually, `cbed` is reset to `false` at the start of each iteration (`cbed = false`). But the mutation changes the initial declaration. The `cbed = false` inside the while loop still runs, so the mutation only affects the very first iteration... wait, no - `cbed = false` is inside the while loop body, so it runs every iteration.

Wait, let me re-read. The mutation changes the declaration `var loop = true, cbed = false` to `var loop = true, cbed = true`. But inside the while loop, `cbed = false` is set at the start of each iteration. So the initial value only matters before the loop starts.

The check `if(!cbed)` happens AFTER the `read(null, callback)` call. If the stream is async (callback not called synchronously), `cbed` remains `false` (set at start of loop iteration), so `!cbed` is `true`, and we `return`. With the mutation, `cbed` starts as `true` but gets reset to `false` inside the loop, so behavior should be the same...

Actually wait - the `cbed = false` is inside the while loop, so it runs on each iteration. The initial value of `cbed = true` vs `false` only matters if there's code that checks `cbed` before the loop runs. Looking at the code, there isn't. So the mutation might not matter for normal execution...

Unless the `next()` call at the end (`else if(!loop){ next() }`) is affected. Let me think about when `loop=false` and `cbed=true` but the callback was called synchronously and set `loop=false`... In that case `!loop` is true, so `next()` is called. This seems the same regardless of initial `cbed` value.

Let me test with an async source - if `cbed` stays `false` after `read` call (async), `!cbed` is `true`, so we return. With mutation, same thing since `cbed` was reset to `false` inside loop.

The mutation seems subtle. Let me write a test that exercises the drain function and verify the `done` callback is called correctly.

```typescript
import drain from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/sinks/drain.js";

describe("drain sink", () => {
  it("should call done with null when synchronous stream ends normally", (done) => {
    // Create a synchronous source that emits values then ends
    const values = [1, 2, 3];
    let index = 0;

    function source(end: any, cb: Function) {
      if (end) return cb(end);
      if (index >= values.length) {
        cb(true, null); // stream ended
      } else {
        cb(null, values[index++]);
      }
    }

    const collected: number[] = [];
    const sink = drain(
      (data: number) => { collected.push(data); },
      (err: any) => {
        expect(err).toBeNull();
        expect(collected).toEqual([1, 2, 3]);
        done();
      }
    );

    sink(source);
  });
});
```

